snippet.textDisplay: @hangender Well, to be fair, they had a Repub. governor in Rudy Giuliani for years and change doesn't happen overnight, so it's reasonable to assume that there are a fair number of Repubs. in New York who were narrowly beat out in the next election by Democrats tired of the scandal and corruption that resulted from Giuliani's governorship. So, if a very small number of New Yorkers had voted, and voted Repub., they might still have a Repub. governor right now. From the standpoint of an outsider, it sounds like a fairly small number of New Yorkers were ready for change. But there IS a contingency Republicans still there. They probably didn't vote, and the majority spoke. Even if they did vote, and even if they were voted down, that's just the way democracy works, and people were tired of the corruption that has gone on for too long in this country, spearheaded largely by one party.
